6. adversus casus ignis remedium: a suggestion based on familiarity with Roman fire ordinances. A regulation in the Laws os the-Twelve Tables proxides for a space of 5 feet between the outer walls of adjacent buildings. However the statute had evidently become a dead letter before the time of Tacitus. After the fire of Nero, one of the precautions taken to provide against the repetition of the calamity was the prohibition of single partition walls; see Annales 15. 43.
